ğŸ§© 1ï¸âƒ£ Network Namespaces
ğŸ”¹ Concept
In Linux (and Kubernetes/OpenShift), a network namespace provides an isolated network stack â€” like its own mini network world.
Each Pod in OpenShift runs inside a unique network namespace, meaning:
It has its own IP address, routing table, and interfaces.
It cannot see other podsâ€™ interfaces or routes.
It behaves like a separate networked machine.

ğŸ”¹ Example
When OpenShift (via CRI-O or containerd) creates a pod:
It sets up a network namespace for that pod.
It creates a virtual Ethernet pair (veth) to connect the pod to the node network.

You can see namespaces with:
ip netns list
You can view pod interfaces by entering the namespace:
nsenter -t <pod_pid> -n ip addr

ğŸ”Œ 2ï¸âƒ£ Virtual Ethernet (veth) Pairs
ğŸ”¹ Concept
A veth pair is like a virtual patch cable connecting two network namespaces:
One end is inside the podâ€™s namespace.
The other end is in the host (node) namespace, connected to a bridge or OVS switch.
When a packet leaves the pod, it goes out via its eth0 â†’ veth â†’ host bridge.

ğŸ”¹ Example Flow
Pod Network Namespace
 â””â”€â”€ eth0 (10.128.0.10)
      â”‚
      â”‚ veth pair
      â”‚
Node Network Namespace
 â””â”€â”€ vethXYZ connected to Open vSwitch (br-int)

ğŸ”¹ Inside OpenShift
OpenShiftSDN or OVN-Kubernetes connects that host-side veth to Open vSwitch (OVS).
OVS then routes or encapsulates packets to the correct destination node (via VXLAN or Geneve).

You can list veth interfaces:
ip link show type veth
You can inspect connections:
ovs-vsctl show

ğŸ“ 3ï¸âƒ£ MTU (Maximum Transmission Unit)
ğŸ”¹ Concept
MTU = The largest size (in bytes) of a packet that can be transmitted without fragmentation.
Typical defaults:
Ethernet (host network) â†’ 1500 bytes
Overlay (VXLAN or Geneve) adds encapsulation overhead (â‰ˆ 50â€“60 bytes)
So, Pod network MTU must be smaller, usually 1450 or 1400.

ğŸ”¹ Example Calculation (Geneve Encapsulation)
| Type               | Bytes          |
| ------------------ | -------------- |
| Ethernet Header    | 14             |
| IP Header          | 20             |
| UDP Header         | 8              |
| Geneve Header      | 38             |
| **Total Overhead** | **â‰ˆ 80 bytes** |

Hence:
1500 - 80 = 1420 MTU (typical pod MTU)

ğŸ”¹ Why It Matters
If MTU is mismatched:
Packets get fragmented or dropped.
You see slow pod-to-pod communication or â€œconnection resetâ€ errors.
ğŸ”¹ Check MTU Values

On pod:
ip link show eth0
On host:
ip link show br-int

ğŸš€ 4ï¸âƒ£ Packet Flow Inside OpenShift Cluster
Letâ€™s understand how a packet moves from one pod to another, step by step.

ğŸŸ¢ Case 1: Pod-to-Pod (Same Node)
Pod A sends a packet to Pod B (same node).
Packet leaves Pod A via eth0 â†’ veth pair â†’ OVS bridge (br-int).
OVS looks up Pod Bâ€™s MAC/IP in its flow table.
Delivers packet directly to Pod Bâ€™s veth (no encapsulation, very fast).

âœ… No overlay or tunneling â€” local delivery.

ğŸŸ  Case 2: Pod-to-Pod (Different Nodes)
Pod A (on Node1) sends a packet to Pod B (on Node2).
Packet goes out Pod Aâ€™s veth â†’ OVS bridge (br-int) on Node1.
OVS encapsulates packet using:
VXLAN (OpenShift SDN)
Geneve (OVN-Kubernetes)
Encapsulated packet travels over the Host Network (e.g., 192.168.122.0/24) to Node2.
Node2â€™s OVS decapsulates it.
Packet is injected into Pod Bâ€™s veth (delivered to Pod B).
So the outer IP header is Node1 â†’ Node2, and the inner IP header is PodA â†’ PodB.

ğŸ”µ Case 3: Pod-to-Service
Pod sends traffic to a Service IP (e.g., 172.30.x.x).
Kube-proxy or OVN rules intercept traffic to that virtual IP.
Service load-balancing picks one backend pod.
Packet gets DNATâ€™ed to the backend podâ€™s IP (10.128.x.x).
Routed through OVS bridge and overlay as in Case 1 or 2.

ğŸ”´ Case 4: Pod-to-External (Egress)
Pod sends traffic to an external IP (e.g., 8.8.8.8).
OVS forwards it to the nodeâ€™s host interface.
The node performs SNAT (Pod IP â†’ Node IP).
Packet exits the cluster via the host network.
Return packet comes back to the node and is DNATed back to the Pod.

